Part 2 — Google Cloud Console setup (do this once)
Step 1 — Create a project
Go to console.cloud.google.com. Click the project dropdown at the top → New Project → name it n8n-automations → Create. Make sure it's selected as your active project before continuing.
Step 2 — Enable the Gmail API
Go to APIs & Services → Library → search Gmail API → click it → Enable.
Step 3 — Configure the OAuth consent screen
Go to APIs & Services → OAuth consent screen. Instead of going straight to settings, Google now shows a Get Started button — click it. This opens a "Project configuration" wizard with 4 steps:
App Information:

App name: n8n
User support email: your Gmail address
Click Next

Audience:

Select External
Click Next

Contact Information:

Email addresses: your Gmail address (this is what Google uses to notify you about changes to the project)
Click Next

Finish:

Review the summary and click Create

Step 4 — Add a test user
After the wizard completes you'll land on the OAuth consent screen dashboard. In the left sub-navigation click Audience. Scroll down to the Test users section → Add users → enter your Gmail address → Save.
This is mandatory while your app is in "testing" mode. Without it Google will block the OAuth flow with an access denied error even if everything else is configured correctly.
Step 5 — Add the Gmail scope
In the left sub-navigation click Data access → Add or remove scopes. In the filter box search Gmail and check:
https://www.googleapis.com/auth/gmail.send
Click Update → Save and continue.
Step 6 — Create the OAuth client
In the left sub-navigation click Clients → Create client.

Application type: Web application
Name: n8n
Under Authorized redirect URIs click Add URI and enter exactly:

  https://yourdomain.com/rest/oauth2-credential/callback

Click Create

A dialog shows your Client ID and Client Secret. Copy both — you'll paste them into n8n in the next step.
